{"id": "duc04-testb-6:5#15", "contents": "Foreign researchers who have worked in North Korea believe that the country's hunger crisis began several years before the floods and droughts of the mid-1990s, and is linked to the collapse of the Soviet Union, which had long been North Korea's main supplier of food, fuel, and fertilizer. The country's mountainous terrain, with less than 20% arable land, makes it difficult to produce enough food, and it has been a food importer for decades, mostly from the former Soviet Union and China. According to Ms. Cheng-Hopkins, \"The country has to come to grips with the fact that this is part of a structural problem and can't just be blamed on the weather anymore.\""}
